library(ggplot2)
library(ggmap)
library(maps)
library(mapdata)
library(tidyverse)

We will use the map_data function to obtain dataframes with the coordinates you need to generate maps.

Check out the maps package to learn more about the different maps it contains!

italy <- map_data("italy")

This is what the dataframe looks like:

head(italy)
##       long      lat group order        region subregion

We use geom_polygon to create the different shapes. You use the fixed coordinates function to fix the aspect ratio.

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = italy, 
                        aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
                        color = "gray28", fill="gray28") +
           coord_fixed(1.3)

This looks bad with this ratio

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = italy, 
                        aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
                        color = "gray28", fill="gray28") +
           coord_fixed(1.8)

In the above, I forced the color so that you couldn’t tell the regions apart, you can change this.

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = italy, 
                        aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group)) +
           coord_fixed(1.3)

You need to have the group variable so that each polygon is drawn properly. Otherwise the lines get mixed up.

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = italy, 
                        aes(x=long, y = lat)) +
           coord_fixed(1.3)

You can play with the aesthetics

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group), fill = "forestgreen", color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3)

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill=region),
               color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3) + 
  guides(fill=FALSE)

You can add points to the plot

italian_cities <- rbind(c(43.769562, 11.255814, "Florence"),
                         c(41.902782, 12.496366, "Rome"),
                         c(45.438759, 12.327145, "Venice")
                         ) %>%
                   as.tibble() %>%
                   mutate(lat = as.numeric(V1),
                          long = as.numeric(V2),
                          names = V3) %>%
                   select(long,lat,names)
ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill=region),
               color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3) + 
  guides(fill=FALSE) +
  geom_point(data = italian_cities, aes(x = long, y = lat), color = "grey15", size = 2)

You can even anotate the plot

This one uses the label function

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill=region),
               color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3) + 
  guides(fill=FALSE) +
  geom_label(data = italian_cities, aes(x = long, y = lat, label = names), 
             size = 2)

This one uses the text function

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
               color = "white", fill = "gray78") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3) + 
  guides(fill=FALSE) +
  geom_point(data = italian_cities, aes(x = long, y = lat), 
             color = "grey15", size = 2) +
  geom_text(data = italian_cities, aes(x = long, y = lat + 0.32, label = names), 
             size = 3.5)

You can also color by other variables, such as population density.

The code below does some cleaning to get the two datasets to align

italian_cities_density <- read_csv("~/Desktop/provinces_italy.csv") %>%
                            rename(subregion = Province)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Province = col_character(),
##   Administrative = col_character(),
##   Macro = col_character(),
##   Area = col_number(),
##   Density = col_number()
## )
other.regions <- c("Agrigento","Trapani","Messina","Palermo",
                   "Caltanissetta", "Udine","Pordenone","Gorizia", "Venezia",
                   "Trieste",  "Milano",   "Padova",   "Torino",  "Mantova",
                   "Genova",   "Massa-Carrara", "Forli'", "Firenze",  
                   "Pesaro e Urbino", "Arezzo",   
                   "Livorno", "Grosseto", "Sassari",  
                   "Avellino", "Latina",  "Napoli", "Cagliari")

italy <- italy %>%
            mutate(subregion = ifelse(is.na(subregion),
                                            region,
                                            subregion),
                   subregion = ifelse(region %in% other.regions, 
                                      region,
                                      subregion)) %>%
            left_join(italian_cities_density, "subregion")

This plot is colored by region population density

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill=Density),
               color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(trans = "log10")

This plot is colored using the administrative regions.

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill = Macro),
               color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3)

You can zoom in like this:

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill = Macro),
               color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3) +
  xlim(12.5,20) + ylim(37.5, 43)

Or alternatively:

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill = Macro),
               color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(xlim = c(12.5,20),  ylim = c(37.5, 43), ratio = 1.3)

Additional aesthetic changes

You can also add extra effects to the plots. I like to use themes. The best two examples are theme_bw(), theme_nothing(), and theme_classic()

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
               color = "white") + 
 coord_fixed(1.3) +
 theme_nothing()

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
               color = "white") + 
 coord_fixed(1.3) +
 theme_classic()

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = italy, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group, fill = Density),
               color = "white") + 
 coord_fixed(1.3) +
 scale_fill_gradient(trans = "log10") +
 theme_bw()
